<section class="about-hero">

  <div class="about-content">

    <p class="subtitle">
      About
    </p>

    <h1>
      I photograph to share what the world,
      for a moment, has chosen to reveal.
    </h1>

    <div class="about-text">

      <p>
        Before taking a photograph, I observe.
        I wait, study the scene and experience the place with my own eyes.
        The photograph comes later.
      </p>

      <p>
        I am drawn to changes in light, hidden details and quiet gestures:
        those brief moments capable of transforming something ordinary
        into something worth remembering.
      </p>

    </div>

  </div>

</section>


<section class="about-story">

  <div class="about-story-content reveal">

    <p>
      I am Fabrizio Vinciguerra, a Sicilian photographer born in 1983.
    </p>

    <p>
      Photography makes me happy because, while I am looking through the camera,
      everything else disappears. There is only the scene in front of me,
      the possibility it contains and the responsibility of representing it
      as honestly as I can.
    </p>

    <p>
      I do not photograph a place simply to document its appearance.
      I look for the moment in which light reveals something that,
      only a few seconds earlier, could not be seen.
    </p>

    <p>
      This approach began with landscapes, forests, waterfalls and volcanic lands,
      but it is not limited to them. The same search can exist in a city,
      in an everyday gesture, in a person waiting or in a fleeting human expression.
    </p>

  </div>

</section>


<section class="about-vision">

  <div class="about-vision-content">

    <p class="subtitle reveal">
      A Way of Looking
    </p>

    <div class="about-vision-grid">

      <div class="about-vision-title reveal">

        <h2>
          The subject changes.<br>
          The search remains.
        </h2>

      </div>

      <div class="about-vision-text reveal">

        <p>
          A technically successful image is not enough for me.
          If it says nothing, it does not belong in my work.
        </p>

        <p>
          I want a photograph to carry a feeling, a memory or a detail
          that might otherwise have passed unnoticed.
        </p>

        <p>
          My hope is that those who look at my images feel the desire
          to stop for a moment and look at the world with different eyes.
        </p>

      </div>

    </div>

  </div>

</section>


<section class="about-quote">

  <div class="about-quote-content reveal">

    <p>
